Ebullient over their legal victory against Microsoft, Justice Department antitrust officials said that they would examine possible remedies to put an end what a federal judge described as the company's monopolistic practices.
Microsoft Corp. violated the nation's antitrust laws through predatory and anticompetitive behavior and kept ``an oppressive thumb on the scale of competitive fortune,'' a federal judge ruled.
Antitrust lawyers from the U.S. Justice Department were summoned to the White House Tuesday to brief President Bill Clinton's legal and economic advisers about a range of options for dealing with Microsoft Corp., including splitting up the software giant.
